Just a styling change — two places currently have this pattern: plot_combined.py (the loss+IoU dual-axis plot) and eval_threshold.py (the mask-threshold sweep). Let me update both, since "median black, quartile band grayscale" applies to any curve you plot this way.
1. plot_combined.py
bashnano ~/plot_combined.py
Find:
pythonax2 = ax1.twinx()
ax2.plot(iou_df["epoch"], iou_df["median_iou"], color="black", linewidth=2, label="median IoU")
ax2.fill_between(iou_df["epoch"], iou_df["q1_iou"], iou_df["q3_iou"],
                  color="black", alpha=0.15, label="IoU IQR (Q1-Q3)")
Replace with:
pythonax2 = ax1.twinx()
ax2.fill_between(iou_df["epoch"], iou_df["q1_iou"], iou_df["q3_iou"],
                  color="0.6", alpha=0.5, label="IoU IQR (Q1-Q3)")
ax2.plot(iou_df["epoch"], iou_df["median_iou"], color="black", linewidth=2.5, label="median IoU")
(color="0.6" is matplotlib's grayscale shorthand — a string between "0" (black) and "1" (white); 0.6 gives a clear mid-gray. Draw order also swapped so the black median line renders on top of the gray band instead of underneath it.)
