This one needs a bit more thought than a straight swap — you're plotting two classes on one graph, and pure black/grayscale for both would make occulter and CME indistinguishable from each other. I'm keeping distinct grayscale shades per class (still no color, but different enough to tell apart) with a shaded IQR band per class instead of separate Q1/Q3 lines:
pythonplt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
class_styles = {"occulter": {"median_color": "black", "band_color": "0.75"},
                "cme": {"median_color": "0.25", "band_color": "0.5"}}

for name in CLASS_NAMES.values():
    style = class_styles[name]
    plt.fill_between(THRESHOLDS, sweep_results[name]["q1"], sweep_results[name]["q3"],
                      color=style["band_color"], alpha=0.5, label=f"{name} IQR (Q1-Q3)")
    plt.plot(THRESHOLDS, sweep_results[name]["median"], color=style["median_color"],
              linewidth=2.5, label=f"{name} median IoU")
If you'd rather keep occulter/CME visually distinguished by actual color (since grayscale-on-grayscale for two classes can get hard to read at a glance), tell me and I'll keep color for the class distinction but still apply black-median/grayscale-band within each class's own color family (e.g., a black median line with a light-blue-tinted band for occulter, dark line with light-orange band for CME) — that's a reasonable middle ground between your instruction and readability with two classes on one plot. Let me know which you'd prefer before you run a batch of these across many models.
